    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the goblin digression! You are absolutely right to focus on the technical mechanics for your exam. Let's get back to the core engineering principles.\n\nThe relationship relies on the complementary strengths of the two materials: **concrete** is excellent at resisting **compression** (being squashed), but it has very low **tensile strength** (resisting being pulled apart). Conversely, **steel** has high tensile strength but is weak in compression compared to concrete.\n\nWhen a foundation is subjected to bending moments (like wind or uneven soil pressure), the bottom of the beam or footing tends to stretch (tension) while the top compresses. If you used concrete alone, it would crack and fail under that tension. By embedding steel rebar in the tension zone, you create a composite material where the steel takes the tensile load while the concrete takes the compressive load.\n\nAdditionally, the two materials must work together seamlessly, which is why they are bonded:\n1.  **Compatibility of Deformation:** Both steel and concrete have similar coefficients of thermal expansion, meaning they expand and contract at the same rate with temperature changes, preventing internal stresses.\n2.  **Bond Strength:** The rough surface",
